Perimeter Defense - Email Security > [T1]: Email Attack Prevention: Spoofing & DMARC

Email Attack Vectors

To secure a system, we must first understand how it can be attacked. Unfortunately, attackers can use emails to launch attacks in many ways, and we cannot develop a comprehensive list of all attack methods. However, we will look at attacks from a root cause perspective. This means we will focus on things we -security analysts- can do to eliminate the root cause of the attack, so we do not have to worry about the attack method.

Regardless of the attack method, attackers must utilize one of three techniques to launch an email attack; spoofing, malicious attachments, and embedded URLs. The following section will explain each technique's work and available prevention/detection mechanisms.

 

We have seen that email is the most widely used attack vector. But, what forms the biggest part of email attacks? In their report The 3 Ts of An Email Attack, FireEye stated that 86% of email attacks are malwareless (i.e., does not involve executable malware such as spoofing and phishing attacks).


Figure - zoom in


Following the approach we mentioned earlier of focusing on high-impact stuff, I can easily say that this module is the most critical part of the course because it protects against many email attacks. Get it right, and you will see a noticeable improvement in reducing your attack surface.


Sender Spoofing

Email spoofing manipulates email headers to fake/spoof what the email recipient sees in the "From" field. By spoofing the sender's email address and impersonating someone the victim trusts, the odds of having the email recipient take actions the attacker wants to increase (e.g., opening a malicious attachment or entering credentials into a fake login page controlled by the attacker). Email spoofing is the most common way attackers lure end-users into opening malicious attachments, clicking URLs, or submitting credentials to a fake login page.


A well-known example of spoofing is sending a fake email that looks like it came from IT support (i.e., support@corporate.com), asking the user to reset his expired password. The victim opens the link, sees the fake company password reset page, and enters his credentials. Once submitted, the credentials get forwarded to the attacker.

The following screenshot is for an email I sent to a Gmail inbox using a free online spoofing service https://emkei.cz/. As shown, I was able to spoof the sender address to appear as support@amazon.com.


Figure - zoom in


Unfortunately, email spoofing is too easy because the SMTP protocol used to send and receive emails lacks an authentication mechanism.  A quick Google search for Email Spoof Test should return many results. The good news is that defenders can use a free and effective authentication protocol to fight and stop email spoofing called DMARC. In the next lesson, we will explain DMARC in detail and see how it can defend against email spoofing threats.
